==English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|geste||idle tale}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|geste||acts, exploits}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|gesta||acts, deeds}}. Compare {{m|en|gest}}, {{m|en|gesture}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{enPR|jĕst}}, {{IPA|/dʒɛst/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-jest.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɛst|lang=en}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|archaic}} An [[act]] [[perform]]ed for [[amusement]]; a [[joke]].
#* Sheridan
#*: The Right Honourable gentleman is indebted to his memory for his '''jests''', and to his imagination for his facts.
# {{lb|en|archaic}} Someone or something that is [[ridicule]]d; the target of a [[joke]].
#: ''Your majesty, stop him before he makes you the '''jest''' of the court.''
#* Shakespeare
#*: Then let me be your '''jest'''; I deserve it.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A deed; an action; a [[gest]].
#* Sir T. Elyot
#*: the '''jests''' or actions of princes
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[mask]]; a [[pageant]]; an [[interlude]].
#: {{rfquotek|Nares}}
#* Kyd
#*: He promised us, in honour of our guest, / To grace our banquet with some pompous '''jest'''.

